14 (2) and (3) of this section and a school district or public charter school has received consent as
15 provided by subsection (6) of this section, the school district or public charter school shall award
16 a high school diploma to the student.
17 (5) If a school district or public charter school has received consent as provided by subsection
18 (6) of this section, the school district or public charter school may advance the student to the next
19 grade level if the student has satisfied the requirements for the student’s current grade level.
20 (6)(a) For the purpose of receiving consent as provided by subsections (1)(d), (4) and (5) of this
21 section, consent shall be provided by:
22 (A) The parent or guardian of the student, if the student:
23 (i) Is under 18 years of age and is not emancipated pursuant to ORS 419B.550 to 419B.558; or
24 (ii) Has been determined not to have the ability to give informed consent regarding the student’s
25 education pursuant to a protective proceeding under ORS chapter 125; or
26 (B) The student, if the student is 18 years of age or older or is emancipated pursuant to ORS
27 419B.550 to 419B.558.
28 (b) For the purpose of awarding a modified diploma or extended diploma as provided by sub-
29 section (1)(d) of this section or of awarding a high school diploma as provided by subsection (4) of
30 this section, consent must be received during the school year for which the diploma will be awarded.
31 (7) A school district or public charter school shall award a modified diploma only to students
32 who have demonstrated the inability to meet the full set of academic content standards for a high
33 school diploma with reasonable modifications and accommodations. To be eligible for a modified di-
34 ploma, a student must:
35 (a) Satisfy the requirements for a modified diploma established by this section and the State
36 Board of Education; and
37 (b) Have a documented history of an inability to maintain grade level achievement due to sig-
38 nificant learning and instructional barriers or have a documented history of a medical condition that
39 creates a barrier to achievement.
40 (8) A school district or public charter school shall award an extended diploma only to students
41 who have demonstrated the inability to meet the full set of academic content standards for a high
42 school diploma with reasonable modifications and accommodations. To be eligible for an extended
43 diploma, a student must:
44 (a) While in grade nine through completion of high school, complete 12 credits, which may not
45 include more than six credits earned in a self-contained special education classroom and shall in-
[11]

SB 1572
1 clude:
2 (A) Two credits of mathematics;
3 (B) Two credits of language arts;
4 (C) Two credits of science;
5 (D) Three credits of history, geography, economics or civics;
6 (E) One credit of health;
7 (F) One credit of physical education; and
8 (G) One credit of the arts or a world language; and
9 (b) Have a documented history of:
10 (A) An inability to maintain grade level achievement due to significant learning and instruc-
11 tional barriers;
12 (B) A medical condition that creates a barrier to achievement; or
13 (C) A change in the student’s ability to participate in grade level activities as a result of a se-
14 rious illness or injury that occurred after grade eight.
15 (9) A school district or public charter school shall award a certificate of attendance to a student
16 who does not satisfy the requirements for a high school diploma, a modified diploma or an extended
17 diploma if the student has maintained regular full-time attendance for at least four years beginning
18 in grade nine and meets requirements established by the board of the school district or public
19 charter school.
20 (10) A student shall have the opportunity to satisfy the requirements of subsection (7), (8) or (9)
21 of this section by the later of:
22 (a) Four years after starting grade nine; or
23 (b) The student reaching the age of 21 years, if the student is entitled to a public education until
24 the age of 21 years under state or federal law.
25 (11)(a) A student may satisfy the requirements described in subsection (7), (8) or (9) of this sec-
26 tion in less than four years if consent is provided in the manner described in subsection (6)(a) of this
27 section.
